{{Main article|2024 French protests against the far-right}}
On 9 June 2024, protests started immediately following the European election results, where several hundred people demonstrated against the RN's victory at Place de la République in Paris and called for a "union of the left" in the next legislative elections and several dozen people chanting anti-Jordan Bardella slogans in Lille. Many Trade union|labour unions, Student society|student groups, human rights groups, and political parties called for rallies in order to oppose the Opposition to immigration|anti-immigration and Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic policies of National Rally, and to promote "Progressivism|progressive alternatives for the world of work". Political parties that called for rallies included the Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party, French Communist Party|Communist Party, The Ecologists (political party)|The Ecologists and La France Insoumise, while union groups calling for rallies included the French Democratic Confederation of Labour (CFDT), the General Confederation of Labour (France)|General Confederation of Labour (CGT), the National Union of Autonomous Trade Unions (UNSA), the Fédération Syndicale Unitaire (FSU), and the Union syndicale Solidaires|Solidaires, promoting the "largest possible" demonstrations.<ref name=":3c"/>

